                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/324.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Ambassador</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-05-01T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 1, 1912—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your April 30, 10 p.m. Since the <hi rend="italic">Buford</hi> sailed the British
                    Embassy here has requested that British subjects be assisted when possible. <pb
                        facs="0923" n="807" xml:id="pg_807"/> Department replied that if there is
                    room after Americans have been cared for <hi rend="italic">Buford</hi> will be
                    glad to extend assistance to British subjects, and has so instructed the <hi
                        rend="italic">Buford</hi>. You may inform the Americans who approached you
                    and the consulates on the west coast that Department will endeavor to have <hi
                        rend="italic">Buford</hi> similarly instructed regarding Spaniards and
                    refugees of other nationalities.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
